‚ÄúIn the 113th  Congress of 2013, I voted against H.R. 152, a supposedly emergency spending bill to help those affected by Hurricane Sandy, but at least half was not to provide assistance to the Hurricane Sandy victims or was not emergency spending.  I would have gladly supported appropriations for actual emergency relief, but I could not in good conscience support something that would have been a spending spree for unrelated programs. That actual bill, however, was laden with non-emergency pork.   The bill authorized a total of $50.5 billion in spending. But, that bill even included such things as salary increases for the FBI, and massive more spending for things that should go through annual appropriations like Head Start. It clearly was consistent, though, with the Obama administration‚Äôs position that they were not going to let what they called a ‚Äúgood crisis go to waste.‚Äù  Rachel Bovard, Senior Director of Policy for The Conservative Partnership, recently revisited the relief bill and reported that, ‚Äúonly around half of the bill ended up actually being for (Hurricane) Sandy relief.‚Äù   Congress should not pack so much NON-emergency spending into an emergency relief bill. Knowing the Trump administration, I feel confident they will not repeat the egregious money grab by the Obama administration but will want the emergency spending this time to help with the real emergency.‚Äù - Rep. Louie Gohmert (TX-01)
